ZS-A45 Yun Huang, Qing Jiang, Yu-Hong Chen, Da-Shan Zhang, Wan-Jing Ding and Zhong- Jun Ma institute of Marine Biology, ocean college, Zhejiang university, Zhoushan 316021, china

As a naturally occurring pyranonaphthoquinone (PNQ) lactone aminoglycosides antibiotic,  medermycin was first isolated from the broths of Streptomyces K73 in 1976 and revealed  remarkable inhibition towards the proliferation of tumour cell lines [1–4]. In recent years,  several similar types of compounds have been discovered, such as menoxymycin A and  qinimycin  A  [5–7].  Two  new  medermycin  analogs  were  found  similar  cytotoxicity  and  suggest  the  generation  of  active  oxygen  species  [5].  And  the  other  hypothesis  is  based  on the inhibition of the serine-threonine kinase AKT/PKB [8,9], which has been shown  to regulate the function of various cellular proteins involved in tumorigenesis and drive  tumour progression [10–13]. Biochemical data implicated medermycin, targeting at con- served cysteines in the activation loop (T-loop), was found to be a selective inhibitor of  AKT [8,9] and exhibited a new strategy for therapy. © 2018 informa uK limited, trading as taylor & francis Group ABSTRACT A new medermycin analog (1) was isolated from the marine-derived  actinomycetes Streptomyces sp. ZS-A45. The structure elucidation of  compound 1 was determined by the HRESIMS and extensive NMR  analysis. And compound 1 exhibited significant cytotoxicity against  PC3 cell lines with IC50 values of 0.81 ± 0.42 μm. ARTICLE HISTORY received 10 december 2017  accepted 16 May 2018 KEYWORDS Streptomyces; medermycin  analog; cytotoxicity

Compound 1 (Figure 1) was obtained as dark yellow powder with a specific rotation of  [𝛼]25 D  + 252 (c 1, MeOH). The molecular formula of 1 was established as C23H25NO8 by a  quasi-molecular ion peak at m/z 444.1659 [M + H]+ in its HRESIMS, accounting for twelve  degrees of unsaturation. The UV-vis absorption maxima at 220 and 430 nm corresponded  to a hydroxynaphthoquinone chromophore [1]. The IR bands indicated the presence of  hydroxyl (3398 cm−1), a γ-lactone (1776 cm−1), and quinone carbonyls (1677 and 1620 cm−1).  Elucidation of the final structure of compound 1 was done on the basis of extensive NMR  analysis, including 1H NMR, 13C NMR, COSY, HSQC, HMBC, and ROESY. Figure 1. chemical structure of compound 1. Figure 2. Key 2d nMr correlations of compound 1. In our continuous efforts for discovering potent bioactive compounds from marine-de- rived actinomycetes, 3′-N-methyl-medermycin (1), a new medermycin analog was isolated  from a strain classified as Streptomyces sp. ZS-A45. Herein, the isolation, structural eluci- dation, and biological activities of 1 are reported. 2.  Results and discussion The 1H and 13C NMR spectral data of compound 1 were similar to the data of meder- mycin except for the monomethyl amino of compound 1 comparing to dimethyl amino of  medermycin at C-3′ [5,6]. Combined with HSQC experiment (Figure 2), the 1H and 13C  NMR data for compound 1 (Table 1) displayed nine CH, two CH2, three CH3, and nine  quaternary carbons.

The 1H-1H COSY data of compound 1 (Figure 2) revealed four spin coupling systems.  Among them, a spin system turn out to be from H-1′ to H-6′. And these protons displayed  highly characteristic resonances for a deoxyaminosuger pyranose ring [6]. In addition, from  the HMBC experiment (Figure 2), the long-range coupling between an N-CH3 singlet at  δH 2.72 (s) and C-3′ can be established. What’s more, in another spin system, two coupling  H-6, H-7 doublets at δH 7.71 (d, J = 7.9 Hz), 7.90 (d, J = 7.9 Hz) indicated the presence  Table 1. 1h and 13c nMr spectral data of compound 1 in methanol-d4 (δ in ppm, J in hz). No. 1 3 4 4a 5 5a 6 7 8 9 9a 10 10a 11 of a benzene ring. Aided by HMBC spectrum, the aromatic moiety was confirmed as a  9-hydroxynaphthoquinone, which was established by the 13C chemical shift of C-9 at δC  158.8, C-5 at δC 182.8 and C-10 at δC 190.1 and the long-range correlations from H-6 to  C-5, C-8, and C-9a, from H-7 to C-5a and C-9. The remaining parts of compound 1 were  confirmed as a pyran ring and a γ-lactone ring, as established by the  1H-13C long-range  correlations [5] and the other two separated spin systems (H-1 and 1-CH3; H-3, H-4, H-11  and H-12) of compound 1.

Because the NOE correlations between H-3′ and H-1′/H-5′ had been observed in the  ROESY data, the relative stereochemistry of the deoxyaminosuger pyranose ring can be  confirmed. And the relative stereochemistry of the aglycone of compound 1 can be con- structed through the NOE correlation between 1-CH3 and H-3/H-4. In the 190–400 nm region (Figure 3), the CD spectrum of coumponud 1 is similar with  that of medermycin (Figure 1), which showed three Cotton effect around 315 nm, 270 nm,  and 205 nm, respectively. The sample of 1R, 3R, 4R, 1′R, 3′R, 4′S, 5′R-medermycin came  from previous studies. Thus, combined with NOE correlation and coupling constant [5,6],  the CD spectra allowed the assignment of the absolute configuration of compound 1 as 1R,  3R, 4R, 1′R, 3′R, 4′S, 5′R, and named as 3′-N-methyl-medermycin. 3.1.  General experimental procedures Optical  rotation  was  measured  using  a  JASCO  DIP-370  digital  polarimeter  (JASCO  International Co. Ltd., Hachioji, Tokyo, Japan). UV spectrum was recorded on a SHIMAZU  UV-1800  spectrophotometer  (Shimadzu,  Kyoto,  Japan).  IR  spectrum  was  obtained  on

a  Bruker  Vector  22  spectrophotometer  (Bruker,  Fällanden,  Switzerland).  13C  and  other  NMR data were carried on a Bruker AM-400 instrument (Bruker, Fällanden, Switzerland).  HRESIMS  were  acquired  by  an  Agilent  1260  HPLC-6230  TOF  tandem  spectrometer  (Agilent, Palo Alto, American). Open column chromatography (CC) was conducted on silica  gel (100−200 or 200−300 meshes, Qingdao Haiyang Chemical Co., Qingdao, China), and  Sephadex LH-20 (Amersham Pharmacia Biotech, Sweden). And the fractions were further  purified with preparative HPLC (Beijing Chuangxintongheng LC3000 system equipped with  an Agilent Pursuit C-18 column (10 μm, 21.2 × 250 mm)). Thin-layer chromatography was  carried out with silica gel plates (Qingdao Haiyang Chemical Co., Qingdao, China). The  spraying reagent used for TLC was 10% H2SO4 in EtOH (Sinopharm Chemical Reagent  Co. Ltd., Shanghai, China). 3.2.  Actinomycetes material The marine actinomycete Streptomyces sp. ZS-A45 was isolated from muddy sea sediments  collected from the marine sediments of Zhoushan (Zhejiang province, China, N 29º56′46.7″,  E 122º16′04.8″). And the analysis of the 16S rDNA gene sequences identifies this strain by  its 100% similarity with the published sequence of S. cavourensis from GeneBank database  (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/). 3.3.  Fermentation, extraction, and isolation The spores were first inoculated into 500 ml Erlenmeyer flasks containing 250 ml of fermen- tation medium (composed of soluble starch 20 g, KNO3 1 g, K2HPO4 0.5 g, MgSO4·7H20

0.5 g, NaCl 0.5 g, FeSO4·7H2O 0.01 g, H2O 1000 L, sea salt 25 g, pH 7.2–7.4 (using 1 mol/L  HCl, NaOH solutions to adjust pH)) and incubated at 28 °C and shaken at 250 rpm. After  24 h incubation, the strain was inoculated into 160 bottles of 500 ml Erlenmeyer flasks  containing 250 ml of the fermentation medium at 28 °C and shaken at 250 rpm for 7 days.  All the media were sterilized at 121 °C for 20 min. The final 40 L of the broth was extracted three times with each 40 L EtOAc and dried  via rotatory evaporator to obtain the extract (2.92 g). The extract was subjected to the silica  gel column chromatography eluting with a stepwise gradient of CH2Cl2/MeOH (50:1, 20:1,  10:1 and 2:1, v/v) and detected by the TLC to give twelve fractions (Fr.1 to Fr.12). Using the  combination of silica gel column chromatography (CC) at a stepwise gradient of CH2Cl2/ MeOH (20:1, 15:1 and 5:1, v/v) and Sephadex LH-20 CC at a portion of CH2Cl2/MeOH  (1:1, v/v), five fractions (Fr.10-1 to Fr.10-5) were obtained from Fr.10 (102.1 mg). Fr.10-4  (56.0 mg) was further purified by preparative HPLC eluting with a stepwise gradient of  CH3OH/H2O (20:80-100:0, v/v) with 0.5‰ CF3COOH to give compound 1 (9.3 mg).

3.3.1.  3′-N-methyl-medermycin Dark yellow crystal; [𝛼]25 D  + 252 (c 1, MeOH); UV (MeOH) λmax: 220, 430 nm; IR vmax: 3398,  1776, 1677, 1620, 1202 and 680 cm−1. 1H and 13C NMR spectral data, see Table 1; HRESIMS:  m/z 444.1659 [M + H]+ (calcd for C23H26NO8, 444.1653). The cytotoxic activity of compound 1 against the human tumour cell line PC3 was inves- tigated by the SRB assay [14]. In the SRB assay, 100 μl cell suspensions (5 × 104 cell/ml)  were plated in the 96-well plates. After a 24-h incubation, the test compound solutions at  different concentrations were added into each well. After incubated for 72 h, the supernatant  medium was discarded and the cells were fixed with 12% trichloroacetic acid over night at  4 °C. Then the cells were washed with deionized water for five times and the cell layer was  stained with 70 μl of 0.4% SRB for about 20 min. After staining, the plates were washed with  1% acetic acid for five times. The bound SRB was dissolved with 100 μl of 10 mM Tris base  solution and the absorbance was measured at λ = 515 nm in a Tecan Spark 10 M Microplate  Reader. The IC50 was calculated using Calcusyn software. No potential conﬂict of interest was reported by the authors.
